{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Bitcoin uses a novel combination of existing cryptographic foot_4 concepts called a blockchain, which serves as a decentralized ledger of all transactions (Narayanan 2018; Moffett 2022).",
    "Transactions are secured through cryptography, with participants verifying transactions by solving computationally complex cryptographic problems in a process called \"mining\".",
    "As part of this mining process, valid transactions are combined into \"blocks\" which are added to the blockchain.",
    "They are \"chained\" to previous blocks in a way that can be cryptographically verified, meaning that nefarious actors cannot alter this digital ledger, thereby ensuring the system's security (Nakamoto 2008).",
    "For a more complete introduction to Bitcoin and cryptocurrencies, see Narayanan et al. (2016)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Bitcoin uses a novel combination of existing cryptographic foot_4 concepts called a blockchain, which serves as a decentralized ledger of all transactions (Narayanan 2018; Moffett 2022).",
    "They are \"chained\" to previous blocks in a way that can be cryptographically verified, meaning that nefarious actors cannot alter this digital ledger, thereby ensuring the system's security (Nakamoto 2008).",
